  <!-- SEO Content Article -->
  <section
    class="max-w-[760px] w-full mx-auto px-4 pb-20 flex flex-col gap-8 text-slate print:hidden"
    aria-labelledby="about-tool-heading"
  >
    <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h2
        id="about-tool-heading"
        class="font-display font-semibold text-xl sm:text-2xl text-primary tracking-tight"
      >
        Free Online Caps Lock Test
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        This <strong>caps lock test</strong> is the fastest way to check whether
        your keyboard's Caps Lock modifier is currently on or off. Instead of
        squinting at a tiny keyboard LED or guessing why your password keeps
        getting rejected, you get a large, instant ON/OFF indicator the moment
        you press a key. The tool reads the true software state reported by your
        operating system through the browser's <code>getModifierState</code>
        API, so it works reliably on Windows, macOS, Linux, and Chromebook. Every
        keystroke and toggle is processed locally in your browser &mdash; nothing
        is uploaded &mdash; making it a private, secure way to confirm your caps
        lock status in seconds.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        People search for a <strong>caps lock test</strong> for many reasons.
        Some want to know <strong>what is a caps lock test</strong> and how it
        differs from a full keyboard tester. Others remember it from school and
        wonder <strong>what is a caps lock test in typing class</strong>, where
        instructors used it to teach touch typists to keep caps lock off and rely
        on the Shift key instead. There is even nostalgia for the
        <strong>caps lock test 90s</strong> era, when clunky beige keyboards and
        loud mechanical switches made a firmly-locked caps key part of everyday
        computing. Whatever brought you here, this page gives you a modern,
        accurate answer to the simple question: is caps lock on right now?

      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        What Is a Caps Lock Test?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        A caps lock test is a small diagnostic tool that detects whether the
        Caps Lock key is engaged and reports it visually in real time. In a
        typing class, a caps lock test teaches students to notice when
        <strong>caps lock</strong> is accidentally active so they can correct it
        before typing a whole paragraph in capitals. This tester goes further: it
        logs each keystroke's casing, tracks how many times you toggle caps lock,
        and even flags rapid double-toggles that can indicate a bouncing or
        sticky key switch. That makes it useful both as a learning aid and as a
        hardware health check for mechanical keyboards.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How to Turn Caps Lock Off (Windows, Mac &amp; Chromebook)
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        On most keyboards, learning <strong>how to turn off caps lock</strong> is
        as simple as pressing the Caps Lock key once &mdash; it sits on the left
        edge of the keyboard, right above Shift. If you are wondering about the
        <strong>key above caps lock</strong>, that is the Tab key, while Shift
        sits directly below. Figuring out <strong>how to turn caps lock off</strong>
        on a Chromebook is different, because most Chromebooks replace the caps
        lock key with a Launcher/Search key. To manage
        <strong>caps lock on Chromebook</strong>, press
        <strong>Launcher + Alt</strong>: this covers both
        <strong>how to caps lock on Chromebook</strong> and
        <strong>how to turn caps lock off on Chromebook</strong> using the exact
        same shortcut. Understanding <strong>how to turn off caps lock on
        Chromebook</strong> saves a lot of frustration for anyone switching from
        a traditional laptop.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How to Disable Caps Lock Permanently
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        If you never use the key, you can learn <strong>how to disable caps
        lock</strong> entirely by remapping it. On Windows, Microsoft PowerToys'
        Keyboard Manager can turn Caps Lock into 'Undefined' or a more useful key
        like Escape. On macOS, System Settings &rarr; Keyboard &rarr; Modifier
        Keys lets you set Caps Lock to 'No Action'. On Linux, <code>setxkbmap</code>
        or GNOME Tweaks does the same. Remapping is also the fix when your
        <strong>caps lock reversed</strong> behavior &mdash; lowercase producing
        capitals &mdash; is caused by a stray remap or a held Shift key. After
        making a change, come back and run this caps lock test to confirm the new
        behavior is exactly what you expect.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Beyond Detection: A Caps Lock Converter Workflow
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        While this page focuses on testing, it pairs naturally with a
        <strong>caps lock converter</strong> workflow. If you have already typed a
        block of text in the wrong case, you do not need to retype it &mdash; you
        can convert it. In spreadsheets, the <code>UPPER()</code> and
        <code>LOWER()</code> functions flip casing instantly, and most word
        processors offer a 'Change Case' command. Use the typing practice zone on
        this page to verify your casing output live, then apply a converter to fix
        any text that was captured while caps lock was unexpectedly on. Together,
        the tester and a converter give you complete control over letter casing.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Why Use This Caps Lock Test
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
